     <font class="TallRed">And more music stuff<a name="108755799164165942">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          I actually think we're in agreement, TuuK, about the talent thing; maybe you just read me wrong. What you said about "clone" bands is exactly what I think is wrong with American music, which is what I was saying when I was talking about homogenizationâeveryone sounds the same. What I meant about new talent (and diverse talent) is that record companies NEED to start finding bands like that, not that they have been (because, quite obviously they haven't). People are tired of the dreck that's been out there for years now; record companies have to start finding bands that people want to pay for, bands that have real talent and originality. They also need to stop signing everyone who's moderately good, because there are a lot of duds out there for the few huge bands that bring in all the cash.<br /><br />Also, I take issue with your assertion that the last time that really great bands were found in a short period of time was the 60's. There's a lot of exciting stuff happening in the post-rock and indie scene right now: bands like Broken Social Scene, Godspeed You! Black Emperor, Sigur RÃ³s, Modest Mouse, Death Cab For Cutie (who've both now hit the big time, relatively speaking), The Shins, Belle & Sebastian... There's a lot of neat new music coming out these days that's very different from the nu-metal vs. pop sameness of the late 90s. Yes, there were some really fantastic bands from the 60's, but let's not write off all the cool new artists.<br /><br />And to Kobold, I know that digital quality is quite good these days, but digital is just a means to an ends (as you pointed out). Yes, 24-bit, 192KHz is very high sampling, and indistinguishable from the original to today's listeners. I was just mentioning that the best technically produced album of all time was made in the 60's, before digital ever hit the scene. I'm not a real analog vs. digital Nazi. I won't break into your house and smash your CD player and replace it with a Linn Sondek LP12âI'd go broke very quicklyâbut I think there's a misperception by the general public that "digital = better" automatically, which is of course a fallacy. Excellent sound quality can be obtained by either.<br /><br />To be fair, there is some pretty impressive home studio gear available these days. Most people can afford at least some decent quality gear for a few thousand dollars. But I have yet to hear a home-produced album whose mixing and mastering can match up to studio work by professionals. It's just a different level. In fact, even though I like their music, I find it hard to listen to Death Cab For Cutie and Modest Mouse's earlier albums, which simply aren't as well-produced as their latest, major label offerings. I just wish that all the neat new bands had that opportunity the first time out, by demonstrating talent on demos and being adequately marketed by the labels.<br /><br />And now that that's out of the way, I have to wait for one of you bastards to post again so I can tell the incredibly ridiculous story of my own stupidity yesterday, so I won't look like a front-page whore.<br />
          <div class="byline">
<b>cless</b>&nbsp;@ 7:11 AM [<a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/and-more-music-stuff.php" title="permanent link">#</a>|<a href="mailto:haruki@gmail.com?subject=RE: E3R POST #108755799164165942&body=Hey cless!">e</a>]</div>
